This son of a gun.
I recently took some promo photos for the very talented @benstalets. Check out his music and catch him live if you get the chance!
I walked with you a ways.
I will follow you into the dark.

Hepburn crossed the Rainbow Bridge this week and I already miss her so terribly much. But it’s hard to stay sad when I have 12 years of beautiful memories to think back on. From the moment I saw her, I loved her with all my heart. She was five months old when we rescued her. I wasn’t expecting to come home with a puppy that day, but when I saw that sparkling blue eye, I knew she was special. She was feisty and energetic and I had to take her to the park constantly to release some of that playful energy. In fact, that’s how my photography journey began. With only my iphone, we began to explore the beauty of Ohio and Michigan. Like a shadow, she was always by my side and it felt like she always would be. She brought us so much joy and her love was indeed unconditional. She was there for us during many moves, career changes, global pandemics and everything in-between. The one constant in our hectic lives.
 
When Hepburn got sick 18 months ago, our world turned upside down. Our lives stopped and we did everything we could to make sure she had the best care. The treatments seemed to have worked and by last summer she was returning to her old self again. Playing, running and being the goofball she had always been. But the victory was short-lived. By fall, she was declining fast and this time there was nothing we could do. She held on a long time as we nursed her and made her as comfortable as we could. Until finally, it was time for both of us to reluctantly let go.
 
“Heterochromia” is what it’s called when someone has two different colored eyes. Some native tribes believed that these individuals have one eye here on Earth, while the other sees in the spirit world. Wherever my Hepburn is now, part of me wonders if she has two blue eyes now? But I hope she still keeps one eye on me as she waits for the day we meet again. She never was the most patient dog, but god was she sweet. And loyal. And just about perfect. If you met her, you knew. Goodbye my friend.
 
Thank you all for the kind, heart-felt words during this difficult time. Even if I don’t respond, know that your support means the world to me.
I used to dream in color.
